TY  - JOUR
T1  - Management in Perspective: Management and Organization In Japanese Industry
AU  - Froomkin, Joseph N.
Y1  - 1964/03/01
PY  - 1964
DA  - 1964/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255235
DO  - 10.5465/255235
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 71
EP  - 76
VL  - 7
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article describes the management and organizational practice by businesses in Japan. Corporations in Japan have little formal organization, less delegation of authority and little reliance on staff work. Despite this lack of an accepted or recorded theory of organization, most Japanese firms follow a single pattern in their organization and employment practices. A discussion is presented about economic aspects of Japanese industry and the integration of social values into Japanese business practices.
AB  - The article describes the management and organizational practice by businesses in Japan. Corporations in Japan have little formal organization, less delegation of authority and little reliance on staff work. Despite this lack of an accepted or recorded theory of organization, most Japanese firms follow a single pattern in their organization and employment practices. A discussion is presented about economic aspects of Japanese industry and the integration of social values into Japanese business practices.
